BoW 2.1 Enhancements for New Applications

Kevin Donnelly (Eliyan) and Morgan Whately (Infineon Technologies) survey Open Compute Project work on **BoW 2.1**—enhancements to the open **Bunch-of-Wires** die-to-die PHY that lives in OCP’s physical-layer workstream alongside link-layer efforts.

BoW has broad adoption from legacy nodes down to leading‑edge processes. The public **BoW 2.0** specification remains the baseline; 2.1 adds three thrusts: **BoW for memory** (now published as an addendum), cost‑optimized **BoFlexi** for IoT and edge-style chiplets, and **BoW toward optical** module attachment. Donnelly highlights **BoW memory**: unlike many fixed unidirectional bump maps, BoW 2.0 made bumps flexible transceiver pairs configured at initialization; the memory addendum adds time‑multiplexed TX/RX behavior—useful when traffic is read‑ or write‑dominated rather than simultaneously bidirectional, and optional “extra” bits suited to metadata or ECC. He sketches use cases: controller-in-memory chiplet versus classic controller-on-ASIC, direct-attached memory chiplet, and stacked slices for very high bandwidth per millimeter—positioning packaged HBM‑class memory over a standardized die-to-die beachfront with attractive power and area versus ultra-fine microbump stacks, and notes industry-standardization paths (e.g., vis-à-vis JEDEC-style memory bodies).

Whately describes **BoFlexi**: fewer mandatory lanes, optional single data rate operation to simplify clocking, minimal link training, leverage of unused pins for side functions, power-mode friendliness for standby/hibernate, and support for **wire-bond** and other economical packages so chiplet partitioning pays off outside terabyte-scale data-center links. Donnelly closes on **optical**: OCP short-reach optical activity and interest in coherent “embedded clock” links versus simpler clock‑forwarded die-to-die when bridging electro-optical engines. He plugs the **PHY metrics** white paper and spreadsheet so BoW, UCIe, and other interfaces can be compared on consistent power and bandwidth definitions, invites participation in the weekly BoW workstream, and points to published specs and the group’s working documents.
